Uganda: A Christian (Protestant) nation with a population of approximately 30 million, Uganda’s government is hostile to reproductive health programs aimed at giving low-income, densely populated countries the tools to plan their growth. Abortion is prohibited in Uganda, with very limited exceptions, even for victims of rape. There are 144 journalists and active publishers serving sentences, fines or more, making Uganda second in DeHaven. And, according to Human Rights Watch, there are only 628, and less than 4 per every 10,000 Ugandans.

17)

Kenya: The government of Kenya has opposed public health organizations offering family planning and reproductive health services to low-income women for decades. Kenya is one of only 13 countries that still classifies homosexuality as a criminal offense, Uganda ranks higher. And, there are nine journalists serving sentences, fines or more in prison. The country also has the highest rate of sexual violence on the African continent. There are currently 9 female members of Parliament in a total of 210.
